c3=A.j0("Green hydrogen is a flagship topic for UPSC. Understand difference between grey, blue, and green hydrogen. SIGHT program and electrolyzer costs are frequently tested in Prelims.","",q,"","The Ministry of New and Renewable Energy has launched the National Green Hydrogen Mission with an ambitious target to position India as a global hub for green hydrogen production and export.\n\nMission Targets:\n\u2022 Production of 5 Million Metric Tonnes (MMT) of green hydrogen per annum by 2030\n\u2022 Addition of approximately 125 GW of renewable energy capacity\n\u2022 Abatement of nearly 50 MMT of annual greenhouse gas emissions\n\u2022 Over Rs 8 lakh crore in total investment expected\n\u2022 Creation of over 6 lakh jobs across the value chain\n\nWhat is Green Hydrogen?\nGreen hydrogen is produced by splitting water molecules using electrolysis powered by renewable energy sources (solar, wind). Unlike grey hydrogen (from natural gas) or blue hydrogen (with carbon capture), green hydrogen produces zero carbon emissions.\n\nKey Components:\n1. Strategic Interventions for Green Hydrogen Transition (SIGHT): Financial incentives for electrolyzer manufacturing and green hydrogen production\n2. Green Hydrogen Hubs: Regions capable of supporting large-scale production\n3. Pilot Projects: In steel, mobility, shipping, and decentralized energy\n4. R&D Mission: Development of cutting-edge technologies\n\nSignificance for India:\nIndia currently imports over 85% of its petroleum and 50% of its natural gas requirements. Green hydrogen can reduce fossil fuel dependence, lower carbon emissions, and position India as an exporter of clean energy. The mission aligns with India's Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) under the Paris Agreement and the 2070 net-zero target.","",b,A.a(["Renewable energy generation (solar/wind)","Electrolysis splits water into H2 and O2","Green hydrogen stored/transported","Used in steel, mobility, shipping","Reduces fossil fuel imports by 85%","Meets NDC targets and 2070 net-zero"],b8),"","a5","https://picsum.photos/seed/green_hydrogen/800/400",!1,o,B.bZ,"GREEN H2: G=Green (zero carbon), R=Renewable powered, E=Electrolysis process, E=Energy independence, N=Net-zero aligned, H2=Hydrogen molecule",a0,B.ag,p,n,c3,"","With Rs 19,744 crore outlay, India aims to produce 5 million metric tonnes of green hydrogen annually by 2030, creating 125 GW of renewable energy capacity.","","National Green Hydrogen Mission: India's Clean Energy Future",a1)
